Here is the full performance analysis of `Truncation.cs`. All code in this file is **confirmed hot-path** (every displayed string, thousands of concurrent users).

---

## Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.Substring(` | 0 ✅ |
| `.IndexOf(` w/o StringComparison | 0 ✅ |
| Sync-over-async | 0 ✅ |
| `.ToLower()`/`.ToUpper()` | 0 ✅ |
| Chained `.Replace(` 3+ | 0 ✅ |
| `params` | 0 ✅ |
| `.Split(` | 1 |
| `string.Join(` | 2 |
| `+ truncationString` (real concat, excl. comments) | 3 |
| `.TrimEnd()` (real code) | 1 |
| LINQ `.Take(` | 1 |
| LINQ `.Skip(` | 1 |
| `List<char>` (heap-alloc lookup) | 1 decl |
| `.Contains(c)` on `List<char>` | 2 |
| Unsealed classes | 3 of 3 (0% sealed) |
| Sealed classes | 0 |
| `SearchValues<char>` | 0 |

---

## Findings

### 🔴 1. LINQ `.Take()` / `.Skip()` on hot path (2 instances)

**Impact:** Allocates enumerator + delegate per call; combined with `string.Join` + `+`, each truncation creates 4+ heap objects.
**Files:** `Truncation.cs:L187`, `Truncation.cs:L190`
**Fix:** Replace with span/index-based word joining:

```csharp
// Right truncation — replace string.Join + Take + concat
if (truncateFrom == TruncateFrom.Right)
{
    int endIndex = 0;
    int wordCount = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < value.Length; i++)
    {
        if (value[i] == ' ' || i == value.Length - 1)
        {
            if (i > 0 && value[i - 1] != ' ')
            {
                wordCount++;
                endIndex = value[i] == ' ' ? i : i + 1;
                if (wordCount == length) break;
            }
        }
    }
    return StringReadabilityExtensions.Concat(
        value.AsSpan(0, endIndex), truncationString.AsSpan());
}
```

### 🔴 2. `string.Split()` array allocation on hot path (1 instance)

**Impact:** Allocates a `string[]` plus one `string` per word on every call — significant GC pressure at thousands of requests/sec.
**Files:** `Truncation.cs:L178`
**Fix:** Use manual word-boundary iteration (as shown above) to avoid the array entirely. On .NET 9+, `MemoryExtensions.Split` on a span is zero-allocation.

### 🔴 3. `List<char>.Contains(c)` linear scan for symbol lookup (2 instances)

**Impact:** `IsSymbol` does O(n) linear search across 5 heap-allocated `List<char>` objects (up to 27 comparisons). Called from the text pipeline on every string.
**Files:** `Truncation.cs:L262`, `Truncation.cs:L280`
**Fix:** Replace with `SearchValues<char>` (.NET 8+) for vectorized O(1) lookup:

```csharp
private static readonly SearchValues<char> s_allSymbols =
    SearchValues.Create("()[]{}+-*/=<>!.,;:?!@#$%^&~`\"'\\|");

internal static bool IsSymbol(char c) => s_allSymbols.Contains(c);
```

For `GetSymbolGroup`, use a flat `byte[]` or `int[]` lookup table indexed by char value (all symbols are ASCII ≤ 127):

```csharp
private static readonly int[] s_groupLookup = BuildGroupLookup();
private static int[] BuildGroupLookup()
{
    var table = new int[128];
    Array.Fill(table, -1);
    for (int g = 0; g < SymbolGroups.Length; g++)
        foreach (char c in SymbolGroups[g])
            table[c] = g;
    return table;
}
internal static int GetSymbolGroup(char c) =>
    c < 128 ? s_groupLookup[c] : -1;
```

### 🟡 4. Compound allocation: substring + TrimEnd + concat (1 instance)

**Impact:** Up to 3 heap allocations per call — `value[..n]` (substring), `.TrimEnd()` (second string if trimmed), `+ truncationString` (third string). The **left-truncation** path at L65–67 already uses `AsSpan()` correctly — this right-truncation path is inconsistent.
**Files:** `Truncation.cs:L72`
**Fix:** Use span-based trimming and concat:

```csharp
var slice = value.AsSpan(0, length - truncationString.Length).TrimEnd();
return StringReadabilityExtensions.Concat(slice, truncationString.AsSpan());
```

### 🟡 5. `List<char>[]` heap allocation for static data (1 instance)

**Impact:** 5 `List<char>` heap objects + backing arrays kept alive for the process lifetime, when this is compile-time constant data.
**Files:** `Truncation.cs:L244`
**Fix:** Replaced by `SearchValues<char>` + lookup table (see finding #3). If group structure must be retained, use `ReadOnlySpan<char>` returning properties or `string` literals.

### 🟡 6. Unsealed classes (3 of 3 — 0% sealed)

**Impact:** Prevents JIT devirtualization of `ITruncator.Truncate()` calls. Virtual dispatch on every string is unnecessary if these are leaf classes.
**Files:** `Truncation.cs:L37` (`FixedLengthTruncator`), `L80` (`FixedNumberOfCharactersTruncator`), `L159` (`FixedNumberOfWordsTruncator`)
**Fix:** Add `sealed` to all three class declarations.
**Caveat:** Verify no subclasses exist elsewhere in the codebase.

---

## ✅ Positive Patterns

- ✅ `AsSpan()` span-based concat — used correctly in 3 of 5 truncation paths (L65–67, L134, L148)
- ✅ Early null/empty/no-op returns — avoids work when no truncation needed
- ✅ No `.Substring()` calls — range operators used (still allocate, but show API awareness)
- ✅ No sync-over-async, no regex, no JSON serialization issues

---

## Summary

| Severity | Count | Top Issue |
|----------|-------|-----------|
| 🔴 Critical | 3 | LINQ + Split allocations in word truncator; linear `List<char>` symbol scan |
| 🟡 Moderate | 3 | Triple-alloc right-truncation path; heap `List<char>[]`; unsealed classes |
| ℹ️ Info | 0 | — |

The **most impactful fix** is `FixedNumberOfWordsTruncator` (findings #1 + #2) — it allocates a `string[]` + LINQ iterators + join + concat on every call. At thousands of concurrent users, this is the dominant source of GC pressure. The `Symbols` class (finding #3) is the next priority if `IsSymbol`/`GetSymbolGroup` are called per-character.

